tyle guide, `Colors.white`, `Colors.black`, `Colors.transparent` are often exemp
t in overlay contexts. However, `Colors.white70` and `Colors.black.withOpacity(0
.8)` are technically hardcoded. The question is whether there are design tokens 
for these. Looking at `tokens.dart`, there might not be overlay-specific tokens.
This is a minor issue at best.\n\n9. Looking at `match_success_dialog.dart`: Use
s `Colors.black.withOpacity(0.7)`, `Colors.white`, `Colors.white70`, `Colors.whi
te54`, `Colors.transparent`. Same concern.\n\n10. Looking at `home_page.dart`: U
ses `Colors.transparent` for inactive tab background. That seems acceptable.\n\n
11. More critical: `matching.service.ts` uses `process.env.CLIENT_URL` directly 
in the gateway. The NestJS standard says to use config files, not direct `proces
s.env` access. There's a `jwtConfig` import but no similar config for CORS origi
n.\n\n12. The gateway uses `jsonwebtoken` directly and imports `jwtConfig` from 
config. But wait, looking at `matching.gateway.ts`, it imports `jwtConfig` - is 
this the standard way? The NestJS auth module probably has a JWT service already
. Using `jsonwebtoken` directly in the gateway is acceptable for Socket.io but l
et me check if there's a standard JWT guard/service.\n\n13. `matching_socket_cli
ent.dart` - uses `String.fromEnvironment('API_BASE_URL', defaultValue: 'http://l
ocalhost:3000')`. In Flutter, `String.fromEnvironment` only works at compile tim
e with `--dart-define`. The app likely uses DioClient which reads the base URL f
rom somewhere else (maybe SharedPreferences for dev tools). The socket client ha
rdcodes this compile-time constant approach, which is inconsistent with the DioC
lient pattern. Also, it strips `/api/v1` - this logic might break if the API bas
e URL doesn't end with `/api/v1`.\n\n14. Looking at `matching.service.ts` lines 
