    think='Let me now check some additional things:\n1. The `ProfileCompletionGu
ard` - does it exist?\n2. The `common/guards/profile-completion.guard.ts` - is i
t in the PR or pre-existing?\n3. Check if there are any issues with the BDD step
definitions.\n4. Check the `matching.service.ts` for potential SQL injection ris
ks (there shouldn\'t be since it uses parameterized queries).\n5. Check if there
are issues with the `matching_socket_client.dart` using `String.fromEnvironment`
instead of getting base URL from DioClient.\n6. Check for `docs/design-docs/api.
md` violations regarding OpenAPI paths.\n\nLet me also check if there are any is
sues with how the matching gateway connects to the JWT auth. And check if `Curre
ntUserPayload` exists.\n\nActually, wait. I see that the entities exist in main 
but the PR doesn\'t include any migration. Since the entities already exist in m
ain, there should already be migrations for them. Let me verify this by checking
if the InitialSchema migration includes these tables.\n\nActually, looking at th
e migrations in the repo, there\'s `20250410000000-InitialSchema.ts` which proba
bly contains all the initial tables. Since the entities exist in main and the ma
tching module just references them, no new migration is needed. That\'s fine.\n\
nNow let me check some other critical things:\n1. `matching.module.ts` imports `
BlockEntity` from `../blocks/block.entity`. This is a cross-module entity import
. The NestJS standard says "模块之间通过 Interface / EventEmitter 解耦，禁止直接
import 其他模块的内部 Service". But importing an entity might be acceptable sinc
e TypeORM requires entities to be registered in the module. However, a better ap
proach would be to have the blocks module export the entity or use a shared enti
ties directory. Since `BlockEntity` is in `modules/blocks/` and matching imports
it directly, this could be considered a minor architecture concern. But since en
tities are already in the database directory and `BlockEntity` is in `modules/bl
ocks/`, this is inconsistent. Let me check if BlockEntity was already being impo
rted elsewhere.\n\n2. The `matching.controller.ts` has `GET /matches` without `m
atching` prefix. Looking at `docs/api/matching.md`, the endpoint is `GET /matche
s`. The OpenAPI contract uses `/matches`. The NestJS main.ts sets global prefix 
`api/v1`. So the actual path is `GET /api/v1/matches`. But wait, looking at the 
OpenAPI diff, the paths changed from `/api/v1/matching/recommendations` to `/mat
ching/recommendations` and added `/matches`. This means the OpenAPI spec assumes
the global prefix is handled separately. That\'s consistent with the NestJS main
.ts `app.setGlobalPrefix("api/v1")`.\n\n3. Let me check if there are issues with
the `matching.service.ts` line 126-147. After DB query, it caches and returns di
rectly. But for cache hits, it calls `buildRecommendations` which recalculates d
istance. The issue is that for cache hits, the score ordering from DB is preserv
ed, but distance is recalculated. This is okay.\n\n4. Looking at `matching.servi
ce.ts` more carefully, in `getRecommendations`, when cache hit happens, it retur
ns `buildRecommendations` which uses `profileRepo.findByIds`. But `findByIds` is
deprecated in newer TypeORM versions. That\'s minor.\n\n5. `matching.service.ts`
has a potential bug: in `queryCandidatesFromDb`, it uses `u.last_login_at` for a
ctivity scoring. But looking at the UserEntity, the field might be `last_active_
at` based on the PRD. Let me check the user entity.\n\nActually, let me look at 
what properties the UserEntity has in main.',
